The mood in Latin, therefore, is the subj. or opt. in the sense of a more or less vivid future, and in favour of this is the fact that a si clause with the pres· subj. is always of future time. The subj. is therefore the potential subj. expressing what might happen under a given 'set of circumstances modified by the fact that the subj. in Latin has acquired the power of expressing temporal rela- tions, which is denied to the corresponding moods in Greek. But though the use of the pres. subj. in such clauses for future conditions requires no comment, the very remarkable usage by which the imperf. subj. is used of unreal conditions in present time yet awaits explanation.
